result.execSummary:
The defendant Timothy M Laedtke was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (5th or 6th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Bond shall be applied and the balance due shall be paid as a condition of extended supervision.  If extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with outstanding financial obligations due, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.

Defendant shall not possess or consume any controlled substance without a valid prescription.  

Defendant shall not associate with any known drug users or drug dealers.

Defendant shall not enter or be present in any establishment/residence associated with the sale of illigal drugs.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample.

Defendant shall take all medications as prescribed.

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.

Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment, full time school, or a combination of the two equal to full time status.

Defendant shall obtain and maintain residence.
